segments.text: No, back to how you became dean.
Well, as I mentioned, I had no great aspirations to be a dean.
I enjoyed what I was doing as an associate dean.
When Dr. Price announced that he would like to step down from the deanship after 16 hard years,
and be relieved of that responsibility and go back to teaching and doing some other things he'd like to do.
I heard about it, never thought much about it.
Somebody pitched my name in the hat.
You didn't yourself?
No.
You didn't formally apply then?
No.
Seldom done for administrative posts of this nature.
that I don't know who did.
Somebody submitted my name.
It probably was some people here that knew me.
I had some former students who were here.
Dr. Leon Russell down at the Public Health Department may have.
I don't know who did.
But sometime along in the late fall of 1972 or maybe early 1973, somebody, the search committee, I don't recall who was chairman of it,
They contacted me and asked if I'd like to, if I would consider serving if I was named.
So, you know, usually, well, I'll look at it, and I sent a CV sometime long late in 72 or early 73.
I never thought much more about it.
Then in the spring of 73, I suppose April, I was invited for an interview
But I knew that they were looking at a whole host of people.
So even I came for an interview, I never thought very much about it.
In the meantime, the dean at the University of Missouri had resigned, I guess not too long after Dr. Price did.
So they started a search committee up there, too.
So along through the spring of 1973, I knew that I was out of consideration, both here and at Missouri.
And I didn't have any idea if I'd be selected either place.
And Denver didn't really care.
So it went on then until early summer, I suppose about 1st of July.
And then one day out of the blue, Dr. John Calhoun called me and said that I was one of three that they had centered on.
So he wanted to know if I would come to Dallas and meet with him and Dr. Williams and a couple of members of the Board of Regents.
And I did sometime early July.
I remember that Mr. Wells and Mr. Wittenberg, who was on the Board of Regents at that time, and well-known to the livestock industry, cattlemen's group and so forth.
I remember those two gentlemen were there that day.
So I flew down and met with them and still didn't know where it was all going to wind up.
but did have a very nice meeting, I thought.
Did they ask you about plans that you might have for the vet school?
Yes, they did.

They were very concerned then about the food animal program, as we still are after seven to eight years later, but they were concerned about that, and they were concerned very much about trying to strengthen the clinical parts of the college, and so then I went on
Back home, really never.
I assumed at that time that at least there was a good bit of interest in me.
And then one day, about middle of July, Dr. Calhoun called and offered me the position.
And so then about almost the same time, I was offered a position at Missouri.
Where in?
Yes.
Almost in the same week.
And I was called to meet with the chancellor and the president of that university.
And I actually didn't know where I was going.
That must have been a very difficult decision for you.
It really was.
It was a difficult decision because Missouri was home.
I had close friends, close ties there.
And of course, Texas A&M was my alma mater.
Of course, we still had family and so forth in Texas, so it was very difficult.
I thought the opportunity for me was a little better in Texas, better resources.
And I could already see the financial restraints in Missouri.
They had been settling in on us for the last two or three years there before I left, since about 1970, in fact.
So finally, I elected to come to Texas.
And it wasn't an easy decision.
Also, I've long since, and I still do, believe that an administrator has a little...
It's difficult, in all honesty, to take over a school where you have been one of the men, one of the troops, for long years.
It's very difficult because you can't be very objective.
You really can't weigh the pros and cons of your faculty.
In other words, you think it would have been more difficult for you to take over Missouri because you had been a faculty member for so long.
Substantially more difficult.
It really is.
That's a good point.
Where here, you didn't know most of the people.
I didn't know them that well.
You still had some contacts, though.
I could be far more objective.
But there are some, as we mentioned before,
Nothing is all one way or the other.
And the counter side of that argument, or not an argument, a viewpoint, is that when you come in from an outside and you come in as dean, you're always the dean.
And you never have close friends.
Because people don't want to, usually they don't want to become very close friends with you.
Because they're always afraid their peers will think that they're seeking special favor.
And so when you come in from the outside and assume a deanship or a presidency, it's a lonely job.
You never have close friends.
I never thought of that.
Very lonely.
You're always the dean.
There's some kind of a feeling they keep you at arm's length.
And I'm a human sort of person.
I like people.
And that's kind of a lonely position.
I've never been one.
And I remember my old dean at Missouri who recommended me for a number of jobs.
And I didn't know that he ever said this until years later.
and I don't know whether it was here or somewhere else, and he sent a recommendation.
And he said, well, he has all the qualifications to do the job, but I'm not sure he can ever be tough enough.
And I found out that he said that later in years.
And I understand it.
I thought it was a fair and very valid observation, but that's not my nature.
Sometimes I have trouble being tough enough.

Now, when you came down and assumed the deanship, did you have definite aims or goals, set up, criterias that you wanted to accomplish, ways in which you wanted to shift the focus or move the vet school?
Only generally.
I wanted to strengthen the clinical program.
That was my main and major objective.
That was partly my objective and partly what I was told by the Board of Regents.
So I have made every effort to do that.
I didn't have a lot of preconceived opinions because I had seen a number of administrators come into an administrative post and start making decisions, changing policies, changing directions,
before they really knew the inside.
And I did not want to do that.
I did not want to do that.

So I came in and I tried to, number one, learn what my faculty was like, what the internal operation was like, what the organization was like, who I could trust, who I couldn't, who would perform and who didn't.
So I didn't come in with a lot of preconceived ideas, except generally,
to do two things, strengthen the clinical program and strengthen the research program.
Because I perceive both of them were very weak when I came here.
OK, we're going to talk about those.
But as we both realize, the major changes happened under Dr. Price with the admittance of blacks and women and a great expansion over those years, especially concerning women.
Was there any residue when you
because of that decision when you came in a few years later.
I mean, were there any feelings against women, or were there having any problems with women students, or anything like that, or new women faculty members?
Well, we've tried to add as many as we could, but they were so scarce.
They hadn't been trained to be faculty members.
No.
There was, perhaps, the first couple of years I was here,
There may have been a little feeling on the part of some of the older faculty members against the explosion in the numbers of women.
I never really felt it very much.
And I couldn't even identify individuals who felt that way.
So if there was, it didn't really matter?
It was kind of hidden, subtle.
But I'm sure there was a feeling that we were getting too many women in school.
But I don't think it was ever a major problem.
And still isn't?
No.
Any feelings that might have been a decline then over the years?
Oh, yes.
If there was a feeling that some of the older faculty members, people like Dr. Bill Romaine, Dr. Jim Denton over in the clinic who, and I don't know that they did, but it was human.
They had been there on the firing line with the finished product.
And I think it was very human that they might have felt a little apprehension, but that's all gone now.
I heard Dr. Romaine just last year, he serves on the selections committee now, and he said, you know, I never thought I'd admit it, but the women work harder in clinics than the men do.
Really?
Mm-hmm.
So, yeah, it's all gone.
It's been really a revolution.
One-third of your student body are women.
Mm-hmm.
And there's never been a system of quotas or anything like that, has there?
Back in the early to mid-'70s, they just started looking at Canada.
No quotas, no nothing.
Never been any.
And there's none toward blacks or browns either.
However, we're having trouble getting qualified minorities.
Yeah, let's switch to that right now.
That's been probably a concern ever since you've come here, like you said, the federal government.
and the state government could put some pressure on you.
Why don't we get blacks here?
I think we've only had one, as a matter of fact, one graduate.
One graduate, and two that ever been admitted.
One was admitted, I don't remember, back about mid-60s, and never did complete his work.
I don't know why.
I don't know if he failed out.
No, I don't think he actually failed out.
I think he became discouraged and dropped out.
The question of why.
Now, through the years, we've had some Brown students.
Hispanics, there were Hispanics in school when I was here.
Sure.
And as far as I know, never any feeling that there shouldn't be.
I think always a positive feeling toward Hispanics in school.
Now, we never had great numbers.
Yeah.
But we've always had some.
They still do.
There were five Hispanic students admitted in the class last year.
And I think that was out of 12.
There were 12 applicants, and five were admitted, which was higher than with the Caucasians or whites.
Well, anyhow, the reason for the blacks, they're twofold.
One, they're not unique to Texas A&M.
No other state land grant school is overwhelmed with black applicants either.
But most of them are doing better than we are.
I think if you took all the 25 schools that are in operation now, we'd be down close to the bottom as far as being able to attract black students.
Who would be close to the top?
Ohio State?
Cornell?

Strangely enough, throughout the years, through the whole years, now I can't say the last five years, but through the history, Kansas State and Iowa State have had more black graduates than any other state.
No kidding, that is unusual.
Yeah, and I don't know why.
I think early on, way back there, when old men like Dr. Evans, who was president of Prairie View so many years, was a veterinarian.
I think way back there, they took a few black men into school, and they did well.
Like the dean at Tuskegee for so many years, Dr. Williams, was a Kansas State graduate.

I think that they kind of got an image early, and a few young black men that would go to veterinary school said, wait, I went to K-State, and I was treated well, and I got through, and I don't know what it was.
But to build an image early on, I guess, and maybe a few eminent men, I don't know what it was.
Now, California, a very progressive state, started a very vigorous black recruitment program back about 70, or maybe even 68, 70, somewhere along there.
And I heard...

Dean Pritchard say at a meeting long about 75, 76, he said we have spent untold amount of faculty hours and finance and everything else trying to recruit blacks and we don't have anything to show for it.
No kidding.
California has a sizable black population.
Pretty good size and it's progressive, you know, it has a national image of being progressive.
This is at UC Davis?
UC Davis.
I think UC Davis have had maybe a few more than we've had.
Maybe altogether they've had seven or eight graduates, black graduates.
But they haven't done very well.
And at least, Dean Pritchard said, compared to the effort we spent, our success rate's been woefully inadequate.
But to get back to- So no one's doing very well.
No one's doing very well.
No, that's right.
Because most of the blacks are still going to Tuskegee.
The honest truth is no.
No one is doing very well.
But unfortunately, we are not even doing as well as some of the others.
Do any whites go to Tuskegee?
Yes.
About 40% of the class is white.
Really?
They only take about 60 a year.
And I think about 20 are white.
So, yes, they do.
They can't get enough blacks to fill their class.
Really?
And they recruit vigorously.
from places like Prairie View.
And we've been, last year or so, we've been working pretty hard trying to build our image at Prairie View.
It's partly, I guess, response to the federal pressure, but I don't know.
Our first efforts were, maybe they were inadequate on our part, but they didn't receive much encouragement at Prairie View.

uh dr bay would go down and present a program on opportunities in veterinary medicine and so forth to a group of students at prairie view and we got some pretty stony looks and not much enthusiasm and more recently we've had dr thomas has thrown his weight behind it and we're getting a different reaction now why is that i think because the president says uh we want to
We want to try to build a prevent program and get some students in it, Texas A&M.
And I think his visibility, his prestige, kind of caught on.
And now the dean of agriculture and the head of biology department and so forth, they began to work with us and talk to us.
OK, so the first one was that no university is doing very well.
That's true.
What was your other one?
Well, the other point is Texas A&M doesn't have a good image among blacks in Texas.
Right.
And that's just everybody.
They just don't think they're...
I don't know.
It's so conservative, I guess, and so militaristic, and so maybe in their eyes, redneck, and I don't know what else.
I'm not a sociologist enough to understand.
But
Black students don't look on Texas A&M as a place they want to go.
Exceptions, of course.
So I think we've had to overcome that.
And I have to be absolutely honest.
I've had an awful lot of problems with Texas A&M.
A lot of things I had to devote my attention to.
The Texas Southwestern cattle raisers were on our backs because we weren't getting enough rural kids in school.
Pressures from here and there, in other words, to try to move ahead.
And we've had an unbelievable problem with our admission system because people can't understand why their sons and daughters can't get in school.
Well, let's talk about these.
This is the next thing I want to talk about.
And these are the challenges that you've had since 73.
Let's talk about these right now.
For example, the pressures.
Well, who are the people that have been pressuring the vet school?
They've been heavy for admissions.
That's perhaps the greatest pressure.
And they've come from every which place, every direction.
They come from veterinarians whose sons and daughters who know that their son and their daughter were far better qualified for admission than they were in the 1940s, 50s, and 60s.
And so why can't Susie or Bill get admitted?
And I understand, but they don't.
They don't stop and realize that there are 500 to 600 highly qualified young people every year, and we can only take 138.
And so why?
They intellectually can accept it, but internalize, they can't.
They can't internalize it.
It's a proud father.
So we've had a lot of that sort of thing.
We've had a lot of pressure from the livestock producers who are saying that what we're doing is educating a lot of dog and cat doctors.
I see.
And that we're not educating young people willing to go back to the ports of the branch, to the towns with the last picture show image, and practice.
Get out to the ranch.
Yeah, it is tough.
In Texas, there's a lot of areas in Texas
where veterinary service is not very good, and the cattle raisers can't understand why the young people don't stay out there.
But they can't make a living.
Or they can't make a very good living.
They have to sit in a pickup all day and drive 30 and 40 miles on the call.
And their wives have to live in a small town with an inadequate school system.
And shopping centers are not much good.
Educational systems are not very good.
So we've had a lot to overcome there.
So the pressures from that group have been.
Then more recently, pressures from the minorities.
Well, in what way are the minorities?
I mean, are you having office calls from?
Corps or NAACP or something like that?
Not any of them.
Have you?

One of the real parts of the people, one of the individuals that's really been on this route recently is a lady from the Houston area, Wilhelmina Delco, who is a member of the legislature from Houston area.
And she'd been on the university over at Prairie View anyway.
So she found a weakness.
She found a little Achilles heel because we haven't had any blacks.
And she's angry that A&M over Prairie View anyway, so she's using us as kind of a whipping boy.
But yes, we've had a good bed of politicians after us over the minority from both, not so much the LULAC group, the Browns, because they really can't build a very good case against us.
We can show them that we've taken a good number of the Brown students that have applied.
But we don't have a good defense when we say we've had one black here since the whole history of the school.
We've graduated 3,600 veterinarians and one black.
In spite of the fact that we can see the reasons, it's hard to defend.
How many blacks applied last year?
One.
That made the minimum.
One young woman, academic score was something like 473 out of 483.
So she was so far down, she didn't get an interview.
But then she reported us to the Office of Education.
Oh, I say she did.
Let me back up.
Somebody did.
I would guess it was her or someone that knew her.
So earlier we were talking about the reporting.
We filed about seven reports with the Office of Education.
Just dealing with that one particular case, seven reports?
Oh, five or six or seven.
Well, a number of reports.
Several, yeah.
Discussing that situation and why she was there.
Justifying it, giving all kinds of background data about our program.
And of course we've had that pretty well because we have learned that we have to have it.
So we can drag out the statistics on the numbers of applicants, number of qualifications, how they were selected.
We've gone to a highly mechanized system of selection just in our own defense.
OK, let's talk about other pressures, not only minorities and livestock groups.
And people were upset about admissions.
Any other ones?
Well, there was a lot of upset about our clinical program.
A lot of veterinarians and livestock people were saying that our graduates were not capable of entering the modern day field of agribusiness and in herd health management.
And there was some truth to their arguments.
Because of the curriculum, or why weren't they prepared?

Well, it's curriculum, and it's a philosophical problem that it's very difficult to educate the young person to handle the individual case, the concept of medicine that we've always had, where the youngster has to first learn
what the normal animal is, what the sick animal is, how to make a differential diagnosis, and then apply treatment, therapy, and recommendations for correction.
So that is basically what the veterinary student has to learn.
Now, as a result of the change in agriculture and as a result of the loss of the family farm, the veterinarian no longer can practice the kind of medicine

that he or she could have in 1950, the kind of thing that James Heratt talks about in All Creatures Great and Small, where the individually sick animal, and veterinarians refer to this as emergency practice, or they use another term, fire engine practice, where you just respond to emergencies, which is what veterinarians did up until 20 years ago.
Then comes the shift

away from the small family farms, either to big family farms or industrial farms, factory farms, whatever you call them, where they're highly specialized and a farm may have half a million or $200,000
chicks or laying hens or turkeys, or they may keep 300 sows, brood sows, or they go to enormous numbers of cattle and feed yards or own ranches and farms.
And so all of a sudden we are looking at herd health medicine, emphasis on prevention rather than treatment.
Well, that creates a dichotomy in the educational process.
Number one, the first thing you have to do is to teach the youngster the normal animal and how to diagnose a sick animal.
Then he or she has to become a consultant, you might say, a medical management person.
And in order to do that, how can you do that all in four years?
And so that's the dilemma we've been struggling with.
And that's why we've made a lot of changes on our clinical program.
OK. For example, what type of changes?
Well, we shifted the curriculum to a block system, or a segmented system, where the old system students would go to school, and they'd have surgery Monday, Wednesday, and Friday.
And they'd have infectious diseases Tuesday, Thursday, and these kinds of things, which kept them on campus.
all time.
So we shifted to a block system of education.
And they'll have five weeks of surgery, or they'll have five weeks of small animal medicine, or this or that.
And in the five-week span, they'll have five weeks that they can devote to an externship and a five-week that they can devote to an elective.
And this allows us to get the students off campus, into educational experiences off campus.
Because you can't teach it all.
On-the-job training.
More on-the-job training than is what we're, yeah.
You can't teach it all on campus.
It just can't be done in a big teaching hospital.
The teaching hospital has a certain role.
It's a good role to learn diagnostic medicine, comparative diagnosis, that kind of thing.
They can learn all about the latest techniques in radiology, nuclear medicine, anesthesiology, all these things.
Especially in the food animal medicine and in herd health management, the student has to get off campus.
So we now have training programs and resident teachers in the Texas Department of Corrections at Sugar Land and at Huntsville.
And we have teachers there.
And now we have a training teaching program at Amarillo in the feed yards in the intensive livestock production.
And students can go there for two to five weeks.
They go to the prison one week, rotation.
They can rotate back through again if they want.
So we've broadened our exposure.
But even in spite of it all, we still cannot teach these youngsters to be herd health managers and livestock disease consultants.
